[49m[38;5;10m+     1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 11.10: Clinical Trial Recruitment Conversationalist
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Regulated · **Estimated Cost:** ~$1.50-6 per inquired-patient touch (depends on conversation length, channel mix, model choice, IRB-reviewed-content depth, and downstream coordinator-handoff frequency); meaningfully different cost structure from the previous chapter 11 recipes because the unit economics revolve around per-screened-and-handed-off candidate, not per-active-member subscription
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is 2:14 PM on a Tuesday. Maria is 53 years old. She lives in a small town about ninety minutes from the academic medical center where she has been getting her care for the last eighteen months. She has a diagnosis of stage II triple-negative breast cancer, made about four months ago after a screening mammogram caught a lump that her primary care physician had felt the year before but had described, at the time, as probably nothing. Maria is in active treatment, between cycles of neoadjuvant chemotherapy. She is having a reasonably good chemo week. She is sitting on the couch in the late afternoon, the dog asleep on her lap, scrolling through her hospital's patient portal because she has nothing else to do and she has read every novel her sister loaned her. Her oncologist mentioned at her last appointment, between discussing nausea management and the timing of her surgery, that there is a clinical trial open at the cancer center for which Maria might be eligible. The oncologist said something about a new combination therapy, said something about the trial being one of several options, said something about a research coordinator who would reach out, and then the conversation moved on to other topics. Maria, who was tired and trying to remember everything else her oncologist was telling her, did not write any of it down. The research coordinator has not yet called.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Maria opens the patient portal. There is a notification card on the home screen, the kind that has been showing up since the institution rolled out a new digital-engagement layer about six months ago, and the card says something like "Based on what your care team has discussed with you, you may be eligible for a clinical research study. Want to learn more?" Maria taps the card. The card opens a chat interface. A friendly-but-not-saccharine assistant introduces itself as a chat tool from the cancer center's clinical research office, says clearly that it is a chat tool and not a person, says clearly that it is not part of Maria's clinical care team, says that it is here to help her learn about a study and figure out whether she might be interested in talking to a research coordinator, and says that nothing she says in the chat will affect the care she is receiving. The chat asks if Maria wants to learn about the trial. Maria types "yes."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m What happens next, in a careful deployment, is the bot walks Maria through the study using language that has been reviewed and approved by the IRB (Institutional Review Board) for recruitment communication. <!-- TODO: verify; recruitment communication directed at potential clinical trial participants is generally subject to IRB review under federal regulations including 45 CFR 46 (the Common Rule) and FDA regulations including 21 CFR 50 and 21 CFR 56; specific IRB review requirements vary by institution --> The bot does not exaggerate. The bot does not minimize. The bot does not promise efficacy. The bot does not promise that the trial drug will be better than the standard treatment. The bot uses the IRB-approved-language phrase "investigational" rather than "promising new treatment." The bot describes what the study is testing (a combination of the standard chemotherapy regimen plus an investigational immunotherapy agent), describes what participation would involve (additional clinic visits during chemo cycles, additional blood draws, additional imaging, a longer follow-up period), describes what is being asked of the participant (specific time commitments, specific procedures), describes what the participant gets (potential access to the investigational agent, study-related care covered by the sponsor, no compensation beyond reasonable travel reimbursement), and describes what the participant might face (possible additional side effects, possible randomization to the standard-of-care arm, the ordinary uncertainties of any clinical trial). The bot is clear, throughout, that this is a research study, not standard care, and that the goal of the study is to generate knowledge that may help future patients, with possible benefit to the participant being a possibility but not a guarantee.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The bot asks Maria a small set of basic eligibility questions. The questions are limited to a careful subset that the IRB has approved for digital pre-screening: cancer type and stage (which the bot already has from the chart-context flag that surfaced the recommendation, but verifies with Maria), prior treatments (which the bot also has), age range, geographic ability to travel to the trial site for the required visits, language preference for consent (the trial has Spanish-language consent materials available, and Maria, whose first language is Spanish, is glad to know that), and a basic check on a small number of clear exclusions (active second cancer; pregnancy; specific contraindicated medications). The bot does not ask the medically-detailed eligibility questions that the research coordinator and study team will work through with Maria during the formal screening visit. The bot does not perform the full eligibility determination. The bot does not promise eligibility. The bot is explicit that this is a basic interest-and-fit check, that the formal eligibility determination is done by the study team, and that not every patient who passes the digital pre-screen ends up enrolled.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Maria asks a few questions. She asks how long the trial is. The bot answers from the IRB-reviewed FAQ. She asks what happens if she has a bad reaction. The bot answers from the IRB-reviewed FAQ, including the contact information for the principal investigator and the IRB. She asks whether her insurance covers the extra visits. The bot answers honestly: study-related procedures are covered by the trial sponsor, but ordinary care that would have happened anyway is billed to insurance as usual, and there can be billing complexity that the research coordinator will explain in detail. She asks the question that is on her mind. She asks whether the trial drug will work better than the standard treatment. The bot says, in IRB-reviewed language, that nobody knows yet, that this is what the trial is designed to find out, that she will be assigned to either the investigational arm or the standard-care-control arm by chance (randomization), that all participants in the trial receive at minimum the standard-of-care treatment that they would receive without the trial, and that any potential benefit of the investigational arm is unproven and is the question the trial is asking. The bot does not say "it is promising." The bot does not say "many doctors think this might be the next big thing." The bot does not say "you might be one of the lucky ones." The bot says what the IRB approved.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Maria, after about twenty minutes of conversation, says she would like to talk to a research coordinator. The bot says that is great, asks her preferred contact method (phone, the portal's secure messaging, or email), asks her preferred language for the conversation (Spanish), asks her preferred time of day, and confirms that the research coordinator (who happens to be bilingual) will reach out within the next business day. The bot generates a structured handoff record that is delivered to the research coordinator's queue: Maria's verified portal identity, the trial of interest, the basic-eligibility responses, her preferred-language and preferred-contact preferences, and a note that she has consented to the research coordinator contact. The bot also writes a Communication record to Maria's chart that documents the digital pre-screening contact, with the appropriate framing that this was research-recruitment communication, not clinical care. The bot does not enroll Maria in the trial. The bot does not collect signed consent. The bot does not represent to Maria that she is enrolled. The bot's role ends at the structured warm handoff to the research coordinator. The research coordinator, the next morning, calls Maria, does the medically-detailed pre-screening, schedules the formal screening visit, walks through the consent document with Maria in person, gets her signed consent, and ultimately enrolls her in the trial. Or does not, if the formal screening shows Maria is not eligible. Or Maria, after talking to the coordinator, decides not to participate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is a good outcome. It is an unusual outcome.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The unusual part of the outcome is not that Maria found the trial. The unusual part is that she found it through a workflow that did not require her to (a) hear about the trial from her oncologist in a brief mention during a chemo-side-effects discussion, then (b) remember it the next time she had energy, then (c) navigate the cancer center's research-recruitment website (which is mostly designed for researchers, not patients), then (d) figure out whom to call, then (e) leave a voicemail, then (f) wait for a callback, then (g) try again because the callback came at a bad time, then (h) eventually connect with the research coordinator after a sequence of phone-tag exchanges over two weeks. The unusual part is that the workflow met Maria where she was, in the patient portal she was already using, in her preferred language, on her preferred timeline, with carefully-bounded language reviewed by the IRB, with a structured warm handoff to the research coordinator that did not require Maria to do the workflow plumbing herself.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The typical outcome, for the more than 90 percent of clinical trials in the United States that miss their enrollment targets, is that Maria never opens the chat card. Or she opens it, but the trial recruitment communication is too jargon-heavy and she closes it. Or she opens it, but the workflow doesn't have her preferred-language materials, so she gives up. Or she opens it, completes the digital pre-screen, indicates interest, and the structured handoff lands in a coordinator queue that has no available coordinator for two weeks, and Maria forgets about it. Or her oncologist never thinks to mention the trial because the cancer center has 47 trials open across 12 conditions and the oncologist cannot keep them all in working memory. Or the trial team sends a generic "we have trials open" letter to all patients with stage II breast cancer, and Maria, who is in chemo, throws it away with the rest of the medical mail. <!-- TODO: verify; the figure that more than 90 percent of clinical trials miss their enrollment targets, or experience meaningful enrollment delays, is widely cited in the clinical-research literature; specific figures vary by source, by therapeutic area, and by how "missed target" is defined --> Or the trial enrolls a population that is not representative (older, whiter, more educated, more urban, more English-speaking, more health-literate, more digitally-engaged) than the disease population, with the result that the trial's findings, even if positive, generalize less than they should. <!-- TODO: verify; under-representation of racial and ethnic minorities, older adults, rural residents, lower-socioeconomic-status patients, and non-English-language-preference patients in clinical trials is well-documented in the clinical-research literature; specific figures vary by therapeutic area and time period -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is clinical-trial recruitment in the United States in 2026, and it is one of the operational bottlenecks that most directly slows the development of new treatments. Trials that miss their enrollment targets are extended, are de-scoped, or are terminated. Trials that enroll non-representative populations produce findings that may not apply to the patients who most need the treatment. Sponsors and academic centers spend enormous sums on recruitment infrastructure and still come up short. Patients who would benefit from access to investigational treatments often never learn the trials exist. Coordinators who could be doing the medically-detailed work of running trials spend their time playing phone tag with potential participants. The math, as a system-design problem, is inefficient.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The previous generations of clinical-trial-recruitment digital tools tried to address this in three waves. The first wave, roughly 2005 to 2015, was registries and matching websites where patients (or their caregivers) self-entered their conditions and demographics and the system returned a list of potentially-relevant trials, often with lengthy and jargon-heavy descriptions copied from ClinicalTrials.gov. <!-- TODO: verify; ClinicalTrials.gov is the U.S. registry of clinical studies maintained by the National Library of Medicine; the registry has been operational since 2000 and contains hundreds of thousands of studies --> Engagement was modest; conversion to actual enrollment was lower. The second wave, roughly 2015 to 2022, was EHR-driven trial-matching where structured patient data (problem lists, medication lists, lab values) was matched against structured eligibility criteria to surface a list of potentially-eligible patients to clinicians or research coordinators, often as an EHR alert. The pattern improved coordinator efficiency and addressed some of the "the oncologist never thinks to mention it" problem; alert fatigue and the gap between "potentially eligible per structured data" and "actually eligible per full review" remained issues. The third wave, starting around 2023, is conversational AI for the patient-facing communication step, in shapes ranging from "a website chat widget that surfaces trial information" to "a portal-integrated assistant that does basic interest screening and warm handoff to coordinators." This third wave is in active development; the careful deployments combine the strengths of EHR-driven matching with the patient-engagement strengths of conversational AI, with explicit IRB review of all recruitment communication.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This recipe is about building, carefully, a clinical-trial recruitment conversationalist that engages patients (or interested family members, where appropriate) in a structured pre-screening conversation, presents IRB-reviewed trial information, runs basic eligibility and interest checks, and produces structured warm handoffs to research coordinators. The architectural patterns from the previous chapter 11 recipes (FAQ bot, scheduling, refills, intake, benefits navigator, triage, chronic disease coach, mental health support, care coordination) all converge here, and several entirely new patterns enter the picture: IRB-reviewed-content discipline as a regulatory primitive, anti-coercion language enforcement, the strict separation between digital pre-screening and formal informed consent (the bot does not collect consent; consent is a coordinator-and-investigator workflow), the equity-focused recruitment design that explicitly aims to reduce rather than amplify trial-population skew, and the operational integration with research-coordinator workflow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few things this recipe is and is not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is the bot that engages patients in IRB-reviewed-language conversations about specific clinical trials they may be eligible for, runs a small set of basic interest-and-fit pre-screening questions, answers IRB-reviewed FAQs, and warm-hands-off interested patients to a research coordinator who runs the formal screening, consent, and enrollment workflow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a clinical-care chatbot. The bot is explicitly framed as research-recruitment communication, not clinical care. The bot's outputs do not modify the patient's clinical-care plan, do not appear in the patient's clinical-care notes (other than as a Communication record documenting the recruitment contact), and do not affect the standard-of-care care the patient is receiving.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a consent-collection tool. Informed consent for clinical-trial enrollment is, in essentially every jurisdiction, a process involving a licensed investigator (or a designee qualified per the protocol and the IRB), the participant's review of an IRB-approved consent document, the participant's opportunity to ask questions, and the participant's signed consent. The bot does not collect consent. The bot may collect a participant's interest in being contacted by a research coordinator (which is itself sometimes called "permission to contact" or "interest" rather than "consent" to participate), per the IRB-approved workflow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a full-eligibility-determination tool. Clinical-trial eligibility is determined by the study team against the protocol-defined inclusion and exclusion criteria, often involving medical-record review, study-specific screening procedures (laboratory, imaging, pathology), and the investigator's judgment. The bot does a basic interest-and-fit pre-screen against a small subset of clearly-disqualifying criteria approved by the IRB for digital pre-screen use.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a cure for trial under-enrollment. Recruitment is a multi-factor problem. The conversational layer is one piece of the answer, alongside trial design, site selection, community engagement, sponsor strategy, the patient-population epidemiology, and the broader trust-and-access landscape. A bot that improves recruitment by 10 to 20 percent against the prior baseline is doing useful work; a bot that promises to "transform" recruitment is making promises it cannot keep.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a replacement for human research coordinators. The coordinator runs the formal pre-screening, walks the patient through consent, schedules screening visits, manages study-related logistics, and serves as the patient's primary research-side contact throughout the trial. The bot reduces the coordinator's time spent on the early-funnel "qualify-or-disqualify and warm up" work, so the coordinator can spend more time on the medically-detailed work the bot cannot do. The economics work because of the time-shift, not because the bot eliminates the coordinator.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a cure for the trust-and-access disparities that drive trial under-representation. A bot that operates in English only, in a patient portal that requires authenticated digital access, will reach the patients who already have authenticated digital access, which skews toward higher-socioeconomic-status, higher-health-literacy, more-urban, more-English-language-preference populations. A recruitment program designed to reduce trial-population skew will deploy the bot alongside multiple other channels (community-based outreach, in-language print materials, in-clinic kiosks, partnerships with community organizations, accessibility for patients with disabilities, transportation assistance, translation services), and will measure recruitment outcomes per cohort, not just in aggregate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a regulatory afterthought. Recruitment communication directed at potential trial participants is, in essentially every jurisdiction, IRB-reviewed material. The bot's content, including the introductory framing, the trial descriptions, the basic-eligibility prompts, the FAQ answers, the handoff messages, the language for declined participation, and any subsequent re-engagement messaging, is reviewed and approved by the IRB before deployment, with revisions resubmitted for review. The institutional Office of Research Compliance, the institutional IRB, the trial sponsor (where applicable), the institutional Privacy Office, and the institutional Office of Equity and Inclusion are all part of the governance, not just the engineering and product teams.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a quick win. The deployment timeline is measured in quarters. The IRB-content-development work is multi-quarter. The integration with the institutional research-coordinator workflow is multi-quarter. The trial-eligibility-criteria-to-digital-prescreen-translation work is per-trial and ongoing. The equity-focused recruitment-strategy work is multi-quarter. The outcome demonstration is multi-year.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing to understand before building this is that the bot's value is not in the cleverness of its conversation. The value is in three places: the consistency of the IRB-reviewed-language delivery (the bot says exactly what the IRB approved, and does not improvise about efficacy or benefit), the structured warm handoff to research coordinators (the coordinator gets a pre-screened candidate with structured information, in their preferred language and channel, instead of a cold list of potentially-eligible patients), and the equity-focused recruitment-strategy design (the bot is one channel among several, and the institutional metrics measure recruitment outcomes per cohort to detect and address skew). A bot evaluated on per-conversation engagement metrics will be optimized for the wrong thing. A bot evaluated on coordinator-handoff conversion, on enrollment-from-handoff conversion, on trial-population representativeness against the disease epidemiology, and on time-to-enrollment is being evaluated correctly, and the architectural decisions follow from there.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let's get into it, carefully.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
