[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: IRB-Reviewed Conversational Recruitment With Structured Pre-Screen And Warm Coordinator Handoff
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why Trial Recruitment Has Resisted Digital Tools, And Why The Latest Attempts Are Different
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Clinical-trial recruitment has been a hand-crafted, human-mediated workflow for almost all of its history, and the reason is structural. Recruitment is, at its core, a matchmaking problem between a specific protocol-defined patient phenotype and the small, geographically-distributed subset of patients who fit that phenotype, want to participate, can manage the time and travel commitments, and can navigate the consent-and-screening workflow without dropping off the list. The matchmaking has, traditionally, been performed by clinicians (who mention trials to patients during clinical encounters), by research coordinators (who maintain lists of potentially-eligible patients and reach out to them), and by self-referral pathways (where patients who have heard about a trial through advocacy organizations, news, or word-of-mouth contact the research site). Each of these pathways has structural limitations. Clinicians cannot remember every open trial across every condition; cognitive load is the primary failure mode. Coordinators cannot scale linearly with trial portfolio growth; staffing is the primary failure mode. Self-referral over-samples the patients with the strongest existing engagement with research, the highest health literacy, the most digital access, and the most demographic homogeneity; equity is the primary failure mode.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Digital-trial-matching tools have, for most of their history, been able to deliver some of this and not other parts. EHR-driven matching against structured eligibility criteria addresses the clinician-cognitive-load problem and is the most clinically-integrated approach, with several mature commercial vendors and several open-source academic implementations. <!-- TODO: verify; EHR-driven trial-matching is implemented commercially by several vendors and academically through projects like OHDSI's clinical trial matching efforts; specific vendor and project status varies --> Self-service matching websites address the self-referral pathway by surfacing trials to patients who actively look, with ClinicalTrials.gov as the registry of record. None of these tools handle the patient-engagement step (the conversation in which the trial is presented and the patient decides whether to talk to a coordinator), and the patient-engagement step is where the funnel narrows most dramatically. EHR-driven matching may identify thousands of potentially-eligible patients; only a small fraction ever have a trial-related conversation; only a fraction of those convert to interest; only a fraction of those convert to formal screening; only a fraction of those convert to enrolled participants.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing that changed the workflow shape is, again, large language models that can carry on a coherent, sustained, plain-language conversation about a specific topic, in a specific language, at a specific reading level, while staying inside an IRB-approved content boundary. A conversational tool, deployed with careful institutional governance, can present trial information in plain language reviewed by the IRB, can answer FAQ questions from the IRB-reviewed-FAQ corpus, can run basic interest-and-fit pre-screening, can produce structured warm handoffs to coordinators, and can do all of this in the patient's preferred language and at the patient's preferred reading level. The LLM is not a research coordinator. The LLM is, in the right product design, a tool that lets the coordinator's time be spent on the medically-detailed work, the consent walk-through, and the trial-management work the LLM cannot do, while the LLM handles the early-funnel pre-screen-and-warm-up work where consistency, language coverage, and operational reach matter more than clinical judgment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The architectural shift is from "static website with trial descriptions and a coordinator-contact form" to "conversational interface that surfaces IRB-reviewed trial information, runs structured pre-screen, and produces warm coordinator handoffs." The bot's value is concentrated in three places: the consistency of IRB-reviewed-content delivery (the bot says what was approved, every time, in every language), the structured warm handoff to coordinators (the coordinator gets a pre-screened candidate with structured information rather than a cold list of names), and the equity-focused recruitment-strategy design (the bot is one channel among several, with per-cohort outcome monitoring to detect and address skew).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A note on what conversational trial-recruitment AI is and is not, because the category contains products with very different scopes. The careful end of the spectrum is structured IRB-reviewed-content delivery with basic pre-screening and warm coordinator handoff: think portal-integrated assistant that surfaces trials to patients with relevant chart context, presents IRB-reviewed trial descriptions, runs IRB-approved basic-eligibility questions, and warm-hands-off interested patients. The middle of the spectrum is general-purpose chatbots used for trial-information delivery without IRB-reviewed-content discipline. The risky end of the spectrum is recruitment-marketing chatbots optimized for conversion, with engagement-maximizing language patterns, with minimal-or-no IRB review of the content, with promises of access to "innovative therapies," and with the kind of patient-coercion concerns that the IRB regulatory framework was designed to prevent. <!-- TODO: verify; concerns about coercive recruitment language, undue inducement, and exaggerated benefit claims in clinical-trial recruitment communication are addressed in the ethical and regulatory framework including the Belmont Report, 45 CFR 46, 21 CFR 50, and FDA guidance on recruitment --> This recipe is firmly in the careful end of the spectrum. The architectural decisions are, in part, decisions about which end of the spectrum the product lives on.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What A Trial Recruitment Bot Actually Does
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A trial-recruitment conversationalist, as designed in this recipe, is a tool-using LLM with a system prompt that tells it which assistant it is, the patient's authenticated context (verified portal identity, demographic information that the institution has approved for use in pre-screening, language preference, channel preference, the trial(s) that have surfaced as potentially relevant via the institution's matching pipeline), access to a structured library of IRB-reviewed content per trial (introductory framing, study description, time-and-procedure commitments, potential benefits and risks, FAQ answers, basic-eligibility prompts, decline-with-grace messaging, future-trial-interest messaging), and a careful set of tools for surfacing trial information, running basic pre-screen, answering FAQ questions, scheduling coordinator outreach, recording the conversation as a Communication resource in the chart, and emitting a structured handoff event to the coordinator workflow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The conversation surface is not one conversation. It is a small number of bounded interactions per recruited patient, typically initiated by the patient (most common pattern: the patient sees a trial-recommendation card in the portal and engages), sometimes initiated by the bot per a coordinator-approved invitation message (less common, more carefully governed), sometimes triggered by a chart-context event (a new diagnosis or a new lab value that, combined with the patient's existing chart context, triggers a trial-match flag).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The bot's task surface decomposes roughly as follows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Trial surfacing per institution-approved matching pipeline.** The bot is invoked in the context of a specific trial (or, less commonly, a small set of trials) for which the patient has been pre-flagged as potentially relevant by the institution's matching pipeline. The bot does not freelance trial recommendations; it works within the surface defined by the matching pipeline, which itself is owned by the research office and is reviewed by the IRB for the matching-criteria policy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Introductory framing with explicit non-clinical-care disclosure.** The first conversation does the disclosure work that is non-negotiable in research-recruitment AI: the bot identifies itself as a chat tool and not a person, identifies itself as research-recruitment communication and not clinical care, states clearly that participation in a study is voluntary and that the patient's care will not be affected by their decision, names the principal investigator and the IRB contact for questions, and describes the privacy posture in plain language including specifically how the patient's responses will (and will not) be used. The patient acknowledges. This is not boilerplate; it is an architectural decision, and the IRB will reject any recruitment communication that fails to convey these elements.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **IRB-reviewed trial description in plain language.** The bot presents the trial information using IRB-approved language at the IRB-approved reading level in the patient's preferred language. The description covers what the study is testing, what is being asked of participants, the time and procedure commitments, the potential benefits (described as possibilities, not promises), the potential risks (named clearly), the alternative options including the standard-of-care option of not participating, the compensation (typically modest travel reimbursement; not therapeutic-benefit promises), and the contact information for the principal investigator and the IRB. The bot does not improvise. The bot does not paraphrase the IRB-approved language in a way that loosens the constraints on benefit claims. The bot stays inside the language box.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FAQ handling within the IRB-reviewed library.** The bot answers questions from the IRB-reviewed-FAQ corpus. The corpus is curated per trial by the study team and reviewed by the IRB. Common FAQ topics include trial duration, time commitments, randomization explanation, blinding explanation, side-effect-management, what-if-I-want-to-withdraw, who-pays-for-what, will-this-affect-my-regular-care, can-I-bring-a-family-member-to-visits, is-it-okay-to-talk-to-my-other-doctors-about-this. The bot answers within the FAQ corpus; the bot escalates outside-FAQ questions to the research coordinator without freelancing answers.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Basic interest-and-fit pre-screening on IRB-approved subset of criteria.** The bot runs a small set of pre-screening questions approved by the IRB for digital-pre-screen use. The questions are deliberately a subset of the protocol's full eligibility criteria; they are the subset that is reasonable to ask in a digital pre-screen, that is unlikely to be wrong, and whose answers are useful to the coordinator's downstream workflow. Typical pre-screen questions include verification of the diagnosis (which the bot may have from chart context but verifies with the patient), age range, basic demographic information per IRB-approved use, geographic ability to reach the trial site for required visits, language preference for consent, prior treatment history (when this is part of pre-screen criteria), pregnancy status (when this is an exclusion), and a small number of clearly-disqualifying conditions. The bot does not perform the full eligibility determination; the bot does not ask the medically-detailed questions the coordinator and the study team will work through.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Structured warm handoff to research coordinator.** When the patient indicates interest in proceeding (and passes the basic pre-screen), the bot generates a structured handoff record delivered to the coordinator queue: verified portal identity, the trial of interest, the IRB-approved-pre-screen responses, the patient's preferred-language and preferred-contact preferences, the patient's stated availability, and a Communication-resource trace of the digital pre-screen conversation. The bot also writes a Communication resource to the patient's chart documenting the recruitment contact, with the appropriate framing distinguishing this from clinical-care communication. The bot does not enroll the patient in the trial. The bot does not collect signed consent. The bot's role ends at the structured warm handoff.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Decline-with-grace handling.** When the patient indicates they do not want to proceed (either after the introductory framing, after the trial description, after the FAQ, during the pre-screen, or at the warm-handoff prompt), the bot accepts the decline gracefully, thanks the patient for considering, confirms that the decision will not affect their care, and offers (per IRB-approved language) the option to be contacted about future trials or to opt out of future research-recruitment contact entirely. The decline is recorded in a way that respects the patient's choice; future trial-match events for this patient route per the patient's stated preferences.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Re-engagement carefully, only with IRB approval and patient consent.** Some recruitment pipelines include re-engagement (e.g., a patient who declined a trial six months ago may be a strong candidate for a different trial today). Re-engagement is reviewed by the IRB, is gated by the patient's stated future-trial-interest preferences, is subject to the institutional Privacy Office's policies on contact frequency, and is subject to the underlying trust-relationship considerations that distinguish a research office from a marketing department.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-language and multi-channel support per IRB-approved per-language content.** Every piece of content the bot delivers exists in IRB-reviewed translations, reviewed by clinically-trained language-services staff and the IRB. The bot does not deliver English-language content translated by the LLM at runtime. The bot delivers content from the IRB-approved per-language corpus.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Conversation logging with research-recruitment-specific retention discipline.** Conversations are logged with retention sized to the longest of HIPAA's minimum, the institution's research-records retention rules (often distinct from clinical-records retention), the trial sponsor's contractual retention requirements, and any litigation-hold obligations. The conversation log is auditable by the IRB, by the institutional research-compliance office, and by the trial sponsor where the contract permits.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why A Generic LLM Cannot Run A Trial-Recruitment Bot
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A naive product approach would be: take a generalist LLM, give it the trial protocol's eligibility criteria, prompt it to "engage patients about a clinical trial in a friendly and informative way," and let it have at it. This breaks in several specific ways, each of which has regulatory, ethical, and reputational consequences for the institution.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no IRB-approved-language discipline.** A generalist LLM, asked to describe a trial, will paraphrase the protocol's description in language that is fluent, plausible, and not IRB-approved. The paraphrase will sometimes loosen constraints around benefit claims ("this might be the next big advance" instead of "this is investigational and the trial is designed to find out whether it works"). The paraphrase will sometimes introduce subtle inaccuracies ("you'll get the new drug" instead of "you may be assigned to either the standard-care or the investigational arm by chance"). The paraphrase will sometimes use coercive framing ("don't miss this opportunity" instead of "your participation is voluntary"). The IRB-approved-content discipline is the architectural floor; the LLM delivers from the approved library, not from its parametric memory.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of voluntary-participation framing.** A generalist LLM optimized for engagement will write engagement-maximizing prose, which is structurally at odds with the IRB-required voluntary-participation framing. The IRB's regulatory framework includes specific protections against undue inducement, coercion, and the kinds of subtle pressure that engagement-maximizing prose tends to produce. The bot is explicitly framed as not engagement-maximizing; the bot's content emphasizes the voluntary nature of participation, the right to withdraw, the right to decline without consequence, and the absence of promised benefit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of consent versus interest.** A generalist LLM, given a chat surface and a trial description, will naturally drift toward language that sounds like consent collection ("Are you ready to enroll?" "By saying yes you are agreeing to participate"). Consent for clinical-trial enrollment is not a chat exchange; it is a formal process involving the IRB-approved consent document, the investigator (or qualified designee), the patient's opportunity to ask questions, and the patient's signed consent. The bot does not collect consent. The bot collects, at most, the patient's permission to be contacted by a coordinator. The architectural enforcement is critical and the language discipline is non-trivial.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of pre-screen-versus-full-eligibility.** A generalist LLM, asked to determine eligibility, will work through the protocol's full inclusion and exclusion criteria, including criteria that require medical-record review, laboratory values, imaging findings, or investigator judgment. The bot's pre-screen is deliberately a subset of clearly-disqualifying criteria approved by the IRB for digital pre-screen use. The architectural separation between digital pre-screen and formal eligibility determination is regulatory, not just operational.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model invents trial details when grounding is weak.** A bot freestyling trial information is delivering content the IRB has not reviewed and the study team has not validated. The IRB-reviewed-content RAG with strict citation grounding is the architectural floor; the LLM delivers content from the reviewed library, not from its parametric memory.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of equity and representation.** A generalist LLM does not, by default, account for the recruitment disparities that have produced trial populations skewed away from racial and ethnic minorities, older adults, rural residents, lower-socioeconomic-status patients, and non-English-language-preference patients. The bot's design accounts for this explicitly: per-language IRB-reviewed content, per-channel deployment with outreach beyond the patient portal, per-cohort outcome monitoring with explicit equity focus, and operational integration with community-engagement and patient-navigation programs.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of population-eligibility carve-outs.** A generalist LLM, asked about a trial, will engage with whoever asks. The IRB-approved recruitment communication may be targeted at specific populations (adults, specific diagnoses, specific stages, specific prior-treatment histories) and may be inappropriate for other populations (minors in adult-only studies; populations with specific contraindications; populations the protocol explicitly excludes). The eligibility-pipeline upstream of the bot enforces the population-level scoping; the bot does not engage outside the scoped population.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of mandatory-reporting-adjacent disclosures.** During a recruitment conversation, a patient may disclose something that, in clinical care, would trigger mandatory reporting (active suicidal ideation, child abuse, intimate-partner violence). The bot is not a clinical-care surface and is not a clinician; the response routes the disclosure to a clinical-care or crisis pathway as appropriate (handing off to the patient's clinical-care team, surfacing crisis resources for active suicidality), separately from the recruitment workflow. The bot does not pretend to handle these as a research-recruitment workflow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of vulnerable-population protections.** Specific populations (pregnant participants in some studies, prisoners, individuals with cognitive impairment, minors, terminally-ill patients in studies with specific risk profiles) have heightened regulatory protections under the Common Rule and FDA regulations. <!-- TODO: verify; vulnerable-population protections in human-subjects research are codified in 45 CFR 46 Subparts B (pregnant women, fetuses, neonates), C (prisoners), D (children), and E (registration of IRBs); FDA regulations include parallel provisions; specific protections vary --> The institutional IRB and research-office workflow handles vulnerable-population recruitment with specific procedures; the bot is not deployed for vulnerable-population recruitment without specific design adaptations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of trial-sponsor obligations.** Trials sponsored by industry (pharmaceutical, device, diagnostic) have contractual recruitment-and-reporting obligations between the sponsor and the institution. The bot's outputs (handoff records, conversation logs, decline events) feed into sponsor reporting per the contract. The bot's recruitment-communication content is reviewed by the sponsor (in addition to the IRB) where the contract requires. The institutional research-administration team is the authority on sponsor-relations posture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of clinically-relevant chart-context use.** Surfacing a trial to a patient based on chart context (a recent diagnosis, a recent staging result, a recent lab value) is helpful when the patient is comfortable with that use of their information and unsettling when they are not. The bot's introductory framing makes clear that the trial-relevance was identified through a structured matching process, names the data classes involved at a high level, and offers the patient the right to opt out of future trial-match contact. The institutional Privacy Office reviews the chart-context-use framing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has compliance implications across multiple regulatory frameworks.** Recruitment communication touches the Common Rule (45 CFR 46), FDA regulations on human-subjects research (21 CFR 50, 21 CFR 56), HIPAA Privacy Rule, and (where applicable) state-specific research-recruitment statutes, sponsor-contract obligations, and (for studies serving substance-use treatment populations) 42 CFR Part 2. <!-- TODO: verify; the regulatory framework for U.S. clinical research is complex with overlapping obligations from the Common Rule, FDA regulations (21 CFR 50, 56, 312, 812), HIPAA, state laws, and sponsor contracts; specific obligations vary --> The audit, retention, access-control, and downstream-research-workflow integration story has to handle each of these.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of the recruitment-pipeline economics.** Recruitment-pipeline metrics (cost-per-pre-screen, cost-per-handoff, cost-per-enrolled-participant, time-to-first-enrolled, enrollment-rate-per-month) are critical to the trial's operational success and the institutional research-office's business case. The bot's deployment is evaluated on these metrics, and the operational-design decisions (channel mix, content depth, pre-screen depth, handoff routing, declined-patient re-engagement) are tuned to optimize the pipeline rather than per-conversation engagement.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What The Trial Recruitment Bot Has To Do That The Previous Bots Did Not
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Recipes 11.1 through 11.9 established the patterns this recipe inherits: input safety screening, identity verification, tool-use orchestration, output safety screening, audit logging, per-cohort monitoring, scope discipline, prompt-injection defense, graceful degradation, longitudinal-context loading, citation grounding, warm-handoff infrastructure. The trial-recruitment bot adds nine structural commitments those recipes did not have.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **IRB-reviewed-content discipline as architectural primitive.** Every piece of content the bot delivers (introductory framing, trial descriptions, FAQ answers, pre-screen prompts, handoff messages, decline-with-grace messages) exists in an IRB-reviewed library, with version preserved on every delivery. The library is owned by the institutional research-administration office in coordination with the study team and the IRB; the LLM does not freelance trial-recruitment content.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Anti-coercion and voluntary-participation framing as architectural discipline.** The bot's tone, prompt, output safety, and content review process all enforce voluntary-participation framing and explicitly avoid engagement-maximizing prose. The institutional research-office and IRB review the bot's output stylistically as well as substantively.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Non-consent-collection scope discipline.** The bot does not collect signed consent for trial enrollment. The bot may collect interest in being contacted by a coordinator, per IRB-approved workflow. The architectural separation is enforced via prompt, output safety, and the absence of any signed-consent-collection tool.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Structured-pre-screen-versus-full-eligibility scope discipline.** The bot runs a small set of basic pre-screen questions approved by the IRB for digital pre-screen use. The bot does not perform the full eligibility determination. The pre-screen subset is per-trial, owned by the study team, and approved by the IRB.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Structured warm handoff to research coordinator with study-team-aware payload.** The handoff is warm: full pre-screen-response context, no patient-restart, structured payload that includes the verified-portal identity, trial of interest, pre-screen responses, language and channel preferences, stated availability, and a Communication-resource trace. The handoff lands in the coordinator workflow with the appropriate study-team-aware routing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity-focused recruitment-strategy design as architectural commitment.** The bot is one channel among several in a recruitment strategy explicitly designed to reduce trial-population skew. Per-language content, multi-channel deployment (portal, in-clinic, community partnerships), per-cohort outcome monitoring, and operational integration with community-engagement and patient-navigation programs are part of the design, not afterthoughts.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Sponsor-contract-aware reporting integration where applicable.** For sponsored trials, the institution's research-administration team coordinates with the sponsor on recruitment communication review (in addition to the IRB), reporting obligations, and post-market surveillance. The bot's outputs feed sponsor reporting per the contract.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Research-recruitment-specific retention and audit posture.** Conversations, handoffs, declines, and re-engagements are logged with retention sized to research-records retention rules, sponsor-contract retention requirements, IRB-audit obligations, and litigation-hold obligations. The audit posture is research-office-aware in addition to clinical-compliance-aware.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Per-trial-content lifecycle with IRB-revision discipline.** Each trial has a content lifecycle: initial IRB approval of the recruitment communication, revisions submitted for IRB review when material changes are made, content retirement when the trial closes enrollment, and per-language equivalence maintained throughout. The version is preserved on every recruitment-communication-decision record.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The rest is largely the same as the previous chapter 11 recipes: tool-surface contract management, identity-assurance lifecycle, conversation logging, scope filtering, per-cohort monitoring, graceful degradation when upstream systems fail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Trial Recruitment Reality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few notes on what makes trial recruitment specifically harder than the other patient-facing bot use cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The unit economics revolve around enrollment, not engagement.** The previous chapter 11 recipes are evaluated on engagement and longitudinal outcomes; the trial-recruitment bot is evaluated on coordinator-handoff conversion, enrollment-from-handoff conversion, time-to-enrollment, enrollment-rate-per-month, and per-cohort representativeness. The funnel narrows aggressively at every step; institutional metrics that focus on the wrong step optimize the wrong thing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Trial-portfolio scale and per-trial content lifecycle is the operational reality.** A major academic medical center may have dozens to hundreds of open trials at any given time, each with its own protocol, eligibility criteria, IRB-approved content, FAQ, and recruitment timeline. The institutional content-management workflow has to scale to per-trial content lifecycles; treating each trial as a one-off engineering project does not scale.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The IRB review cycle is the timeline reality.** IRB review cycles are typically multi-week, with potential additional review rounds for revisions. Material changes to recruitment communication require IRB review; the bot's content management has to plan for this. Treating the IRB as an after-launch review step is a deployment risk; the IRB is involved from day one.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The equity-and-representation reality is structural and is not solved by AI.** Trial-population skew is driven by access disparities, trust disparities, language disparities, socioeconomic disparities, geographic disparities, and historical disparities (including the historical mistreatment of specific populations in research, which has produced specific and well-founded skepticism). <!-- TODO: verify; the historical context for under-representation of racial and ethnic minorities in U.S. clinical trials includes documented incidents of unethical research conduct involving specific populations, including the U.S. Public Health Service Syphilis Study at Tuskegee, the Henrietta Lacks case, and others; specific historical analysis varies --> A bot that operates only in English in an authenticated patient portal will not address most of these disparities; the bot has to be deployed alongside other channels and other strategies.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The clinical-care-versus-research distinction is critical and is non-trivial to communicate.** Patients sometimes confuse research participation with clinical care, and they sometimes confuse opting in to research with opting in to a higher level of care. The bot's introductory framing, ongoing reminders, and handoff messaging maintain the distinction; the institutional research-office reviews the framing carefully, and the IRB enforces the regulatory floor.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The "therapeutic misconception" is a documented and persistent challenge.** The therapeutic misconception is the tendency of trial participants (and prospective participants) to believe that trial participation is more like clinical care than it is, including specifically the belief that the investigational treatment is more likely to work than is supported by the evidence. <!-- TODO: verify; the therapeutic misconception is a well-documented phenomenon in clinical-research ethics, with a substantial body of literature characterizing its prevalence, its drivers, and the communication strategies that may mitigate it --> The bot's content discipline is partly a response to this: avoiding language that exaggerates benefit, emphasizing the investigational nature of trial therapies, and clearly framing randomization, blinding, and the possibility of standard-care assignment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The trust-and-access reality varies by population and by historical context.** Some populations have well-founded skepticism about clinical research that is rooted in documented historical mistreatment; other populations have access barriers that are more structural (transportation, time off work, child care, language access). The bot's deployment cannot solve trust problems, but the bot's design can avoid amplifying them: explicit voluntary-participation framing, transparency about how the patient was identified, clear opt-out pathways, and integration with community-engagement and trust-building programs.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The coordinator-workflow integration is the operational hinge.** The bot's value depends on the coordinator workflow ingesting handoff records efficiently, contacting patients in their preferred language and channel within the timeframe the patient expects, running the medically-detailed pre-screening, and walking the patient through consent. A bot that produces handoff records faster than the coordinator workflow can absorb them produces queue depth, not enrolled participants. The institutional research-administration team is the authority on coordinator-staffing and workflow-integration.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Sponsor-contract dynamics affect deployment decisions.** For industry-sponsored trials, the sponsor has a contractual interest in recruitment communication, recruitment timelines, and recruitment-conversion metrics. The bot's deployment is reviewed by the institutional research-administration team and (per the contract) the sponsor. Sponsor-marketing pressures sometimes push toward engagement-maximizing language; the IRB and the institutional research-office push back against this; the equilibrium is institution-specific.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The patient-portal-as-only-channel approach amplifies access disparities.** The portal channel reaches patients with authenticated digital access, which is correlated with higher socioeconomic status, higher health literacy, more urban geography, and English-language preference. A recruitment program designed to reduce skew deploys the bot in additional channels: in-clinic kiosks, SMS for patients who prefer SMS (with appropriate consent), partnerships with community organizations, in-language print materials, community-based outreach, transportation assistance, and language-access services.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome attribution for recruitment effectiveness is multi-trial and multi-quarter work.** A single trial's enrollment metrics can be noisy. The institution's recruitment-bot deployment effectiveness is observable across trials and across quarters, with appropriate caution about confounders (trial difficulty, trial timing, sponsor changes, principal-investigator changes, broader recruitment-environment changes). The institutional research-administration team is the authority on attribution.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Liability exposure is meaningfully different from clinical-care bots.** A bot that delivers IRB-non-approved recruitment content, that promises efficacy, that pressures patients to participate, that fails to maintain the clinical-care-versus-research distinction, or that bypasses the consent-process protections is exposing the institution to IRB-action, sponsor-contract, and (in the worst case) federal-regulator exposure. The institutional research-administration team, the IRB, and the institutional General Counsel are all part of the policy review.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where The Field Has Moved
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few practical updates worth knowing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **EHR-driven trial-matching is mature and is the most clinically-integrated approach.** Several mature commercial vendors and several academic open-source projects implement EHR-driven trial-matching, surfacing potentially-eligible patients to clinicians or coordinators. <!-- TODO: verify; mature EHR-driven trial-matching solutions exist commercially and academically with varying levels of EHR integration, eligibility-criteria expressiveness, and clinical-workflow integration; specific products and projects vary --> The conversational layer (this recipe) is the patient-engagement step that complements the matching pipeline.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **ClinicalTrials.gov is the U.S. registry of record.** ClinicalTrials.gov is maintained by the National Library of Medicine and contains structured data on hundreds of thousands of studies, with eligibility criteria, contact information, and study status. <!-- TODO: verify; ClinicalTrials.gov has been operational since 2000; the registry contains hundreds of thousands of studies; specific counts and submission requirements vary --> The bot's surface may include trials registered on ClinicalTrials.gov, with the per-trial content (descriptions, FAQ, pre-screen) reviewed by the IRB regardless of the registry information.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Decentralized clinical trials and remote-monitoring trends affect recruitment dynamics.** Many trials, particularly post-2020, have decentralized elements (remote consent, remote monitoring, fewer in-person site visits). Decentralized elements expand the geographic reach of recruitment but introduce their own engagement-and-consent challenges. The bot's design accommodates decentralized-trial workflows where applicable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity-focused recruitment is a regulatory and institutional priority.** The FDA, the NIH, and many institutional research offices have explicit equity-focused recruitment requirements, with diversity action plans for sponsored trials and per-cohort enrollment monitoring. <!-- TODO: verify; the FDA has issued guidance on enhancing diversity in clinical trial populations including draft and final guidance documents; the NIH has policies on inclusion of women and minorities in research; specific provisions vary --> The bot's per-cohort outcome monitoring is part of this institutional discipline.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Tool-using LLMs handle structured pre-screen and IRB-content delivery well when grounded carefully.** The function-calling pattern from the previous chapter 11 recipes maps to trial-recruitment. The LLM produces tool calls that retrieve trial content, retrieve FAQ content, retrieve pre-screen prompts, record pre-screen responses, propose coordinator handoffs, log decline events, and post events for downstream operations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy is mature for the trial-matching layer; the conversational layer is more nascent.** Several mature commercial vendors offer trial-matching products integrated with major EHRs; the conversational-recruitment layer is a more recent product category, with both commercial vendors and institutional in-house builds. Most major institutions deploying in this space run a hybrid: partner with a vendor for the EHR-integrated trial-matching pipeline, build the conversational layer on the institution's preferred LLM platform, and integrate with the institution's research-coordinator workflow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
